Boil a #pot{} of water with a @salt{pinch}. Cut the @New Potatoes{2} into quarters. Cut off the root and the green leafy part from the @Leek{4}. Slice your leek in half lengthways and then very, very thinly slice widthways.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add your leek. Cook for around ~{10%minutes} until soft. Remove from the heat.

Lay each @British Chicken Breasts{4} on a #chopping board{} and slice into it from the side. Open it up like a book. You've now butterflied your chicken!

Set your #grill{} to high heat. Rub a little bit of @olive oil{} onto each chicken breast. Season with a little pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch} and lay on a #baking tray{}. Place under your grill on the highest shelf for ~{5-6%minutes} on one side, then take the tray out from under your grill, turn your chicken over and pop back under for another ~{5-6%minutes}.

> The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Whilst your chicken is grilling, add your potatoes to the #pot{} of boiling water for ~{10%minutes}.

> The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Once they are cooked, drain them and return to the pot off the heat.

Crumble the @Feta Cheese{2}(crumbled) into your cooled leek mixture. Taste the mixture and add a bit of @salt{} and @black pepper{} if necessary.

> Feta is pretty salty already, so make sure you taste as you go to get the seasoning just right.

Spread your leek mixture over the top of your chicken and put back under your grill. Cook for another minute or two until the top is nice and golden.

Once drained, toss your potatoes in a little @?butter{} or @?olive oil{}. Sprinkle over a little @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Finely chop the @Mint{1} leaves and sprinkle them over your potatoes too. Serve with your chicken on the side and savour!